    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-01-22T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-01-22T04:00:00-05:00" n="226"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d226">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.22761/20: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-01-22T12:00:00+03:00"
                            >January 22, 1940—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received January 22—8:45
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>89. During an interview at the Foreign Office yesterday Potemkin<note n="55"
                        xml:id="d226fn55">Vladimir Petrovich Potemkin, Assistant People’s Commissar
                        for Foreign Affairs of the Soviet Union until March 1, 1940.</note> brought
                    to my attention two recent developments which appear to have been deeply
                    resented by the Soviet Government. The first is the exclusion of Soviet
                    representatives from the Wright Airplane factories, an act which Potemkin
                    insisted was discriminatory. The second is a public address alleged to have been
                    made recently by Assistant Secretary of War Johnson<note n="56"
                        xml:id="d226fn56">Speech by Louis Johnson before the New York State Bankers’
                        Association at New York City on January 15; see <hi rend="italic">New York
                            Times</hi>, January 16, 1940, p. 13, and memorandum by the Secretary of
                        State, February 1, <ref target="#pg_250">p. 250</ref>.</note> in the course
                    of which Potemkin asserted, Johnson had made remarks derogatory to the Soviet
                    Union and to the honor of the Soviet Army. Potemkin was especially bitter and
                    caustic on this subject. As I had no knowledge whatsoever of the address I
                    contented myself with a reminder that freedom of speech prevails in the United
                    States.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
